# SubsTrack Conventions

## Project Context

SubsTrack is an open-source Next.js app for managing shared subscriptions. Read `AGENTS.md` at the project root for the full directory map and architecture.

Detailed docs:
- `docs/PLAN.md` — architecture plan, feature roadmap, billing modes
- `docs/data-models.md` — Mongoose schema documentation
- `docs/api-design.md` — API route reference

## Code Style

- Comments: start with lowercase, no trailing period (e.g., `// calculate member share`)
- Use TypeScript strict mode everywhere
- Prefer `const` over `let`, never use `var`
- Use named exports, not default exports (exception: Next.js pages)
- Import alias: `@/*` maps to `src/*`

## API Routes

- Always validate request body with Zod before processing
- Check auth with `auth()` from `@/lib/auth` on protected routes
- Return `{ data: ... }` on success
- Return `{ error: { code, message, details? } }` on failure
- Use standard HTTP status codes

## Database

- Mongoose models in `src/models/`, re-exported from `src/models/index.ts`
- Always call `dbConnect()` from `@/lib/db/mongoose` before model operations in API routes
- Use Mongoose's built-in validation plus Zod for request validation

## Components

- Use shadcn/ui for primitive components (`src/components/ui/`)
- Feature-specific components in `src/components/features/<feature>/`
- Layout components in `src/components/layout/`
- Prefer server components, use `'use client'` only when needed

## Environment

- All secrets via environment variables, never hardcode
- Reference `.env.example` for the full variable list
- Use `process.env.VARIABLE` with runtime checks

## Notifications

- Email templates in `src/lib/email/templates/` as React Email components
- Telegram helpers in `src/lib/telegram/`
- Unified dispatch through `src/lib/notifications/service.ts`
